segments.text: We'd go to Bryan, or we'd go to Navasota, or the other town down there.
Huntsville, maybe?
No, no.
Huntsville was too difficult to get to.
Navasota and .
Wellburn, it's between, but that's not even a town.
No, there's two towns there.
You had pretty good train connections to Navasota, did you?
Oh, yeah, perfect.
And on the Bryan, I presume you rode the trolley.
Yeah.
Was it electric when you were there, or was it gasoline?
No, I believe it was electric.
Did you go to Bryan very often?
No.
Well, as a freshman, I imagine you wouldn't go.
You would not have been able to go as often as .. Well, I didn't want to go.
There wasn't anything to go for.
What was the attitude of the students to the administration?
This would have been both to President Bezell and to the commandant.
Very good, very good.
Who was the commandant?
Was Ike Ashburn there while you were there?
Yeah, he was there, but I don't believe he was commandant.
He was commandant, and he had been there for a number of years.
Was he an annual head?
Was it money changed to leave by G. Brown?
No.
Brown was their hill?
No.
OK, those are two that were about that period.
It must have been a high casualty.
I bet you.
A high casualty.
That's who it was.
One of the things that I feel that makes A&M an interesting school and somewhat unique in the number of traditions that are carried on
at this point largely through the Corps of Cadets, but in a sense by the whole student body.
And that's such things as yell practice, silver taps, the bonfire, the annual muster, and so forth.
Do you recall any of these being carried on while you were there?
Oh, yeah, the bonfire.
Oh, you can't miss that.
What kind of bonfire did you build while you were there?
Just old trees and things.
We built up some big ones down by the Y. Oh, terrific.
Where did you have your bonfire?
Down by the Y.
That would have been across from the drill field then?
Well, no.
Mitchell, in there between Mitchell and the Y. Oh, OK.
Nowadays, they build them over on the inner mural.
Oh, let's see.
It's changed up so much.
It used to be those streets, pretty narrow.
There wasn't all that finery.
We didn't have much finery.
Pretty plain.
I've seen pictures of the campus at that point.
Were there any students living in tents during the year or so that you were there?
I don't think so.
You know, I hear some talk and everything, but I don't think so.
I don't think there's anyone in tents when I was there.
Did you have a muster?
Oh, yeah.
In April, the same day that they have the muster today.
Yeah, yeah, you bet.
And
At various times, we know that there were a few girls who would attend classes.
These would be daughters or sisters or something, a faculty member.
Were there any girls in any of the classes when you were there?
Quite a few girls worked there, but none of them went to any classes with me.
We know that a lot of times the students had a part-time job.
And I know you had a good bit of experience working in your father's establishment.
Did you ever have a job while you were at school the year you were there?
As far as I'm concerned, there wasn't anything I could do.
What I mean, there wasn't anything available for me.
I see.
Have you found who the commandant was?
This is probably the... You talk about a fine man, that J.W.
Grace.
He was one of the nicest looking men.
That Tim Griesenbeck was something.
He was a football player.
That's the Longhorn staff there, I see.
Yeah, Brazil.
Crane.
Colonel Crane was commandant.
He had been there earlier, I believe.
Yeah, but he left, I guess, in 17.
Yes, I remember him.
He was quite old.
Earlier, you indicated that in about October of 1918,
Your father calls you home because of an illness of your brother, and you never went back to school after that.
Right.
When you went back home then, did you go back to work for your father?
No, I went to farming.
My brother had about 200 acres of wheat that hadn't quite finished planting, and I just took over, and I guess I farmed for...
Two years.
This was in the vicinity of Wills Point?
In Wills Point.
Yeah, two miles out.
So you did wheat farming for two years.
And cotton.
And cotton.
What did you do after that tenure?
I left and went over to Cooper, Delta County, and went to work for a contractor hauling with mules and wagon hauling,
concrete aggregate to build the county bridges.
And that's the time that I met Mr. P.B.
Keller, who was Helen Keller's brother.
He became the vice president of Gifford Hill for so many years, a real fine man.
For how long did you work?
Just one year.
One year.
Then I came back home and farmed two years.
Then I went to work for Gifford Hill and Company.
Okay.
Now, was Gifford Hill, was that a Mr. Gifford and a Mr. Hill?
Right.
That's right.
Was the Hill one of your brothers?
Right.
Which one was that?
Birch, the oldest one.
One was 16.
He was class of 16.
And did you work, how long did you work for Gifford Hill?
Well I started to work for him the first day of July and Gifford Hill made the corporation the 10th of July and I worked for him till the fifth day of January, 32.
And then I bought

I was superintendent in Louisiana through the long days, and we were taking script for money, and I bought 30 head of mules, a shovel, a road camp, a tent, you know, where the people lived, and a cook shack, Fresno's, blacksmith shop, all for $1,500.
I bought the job and all.
and the man just got in his car and drove across.
Didn't go down the road.
He went right out across the woods.
And 32 was a very bad year financially.
There just wasn't any money.
Well, was Gifford Hill primarily a road construction?
No.
Railroad and sand and gravel.
Railroad.
I was the only one that did the road construction.
I subbed from them, see, and that's the reason I never owned any stock in Gifford Hill, any part of it, so I could trade with my brother at arm length.
So in 32, then, you bought out.
Right.
What name did you give to your company when you bought out?
No, I worked in Gifford Hill's name.
They were supposed to own it.
I was just superintendent.
I see.
You bought it in their name.
No, I bought it in my name, but as far as the record's concerned, we had two sets of books.
Gifford Hill had one in the Dallas office, and I had my own in the field.
But see, that way, at that time, the engineers were rather...
I'd say slightly Nixon, pro-Nixon, they had to hand out.
And as it was, as I was superintendent, I had no means of giving them any money.
They couldn't get to Dallas, the Dallas office.
So that went on from 1932 to 1948.
And my brother never closed his door in the office up there.
It was always open.
unless it was something special.
So one day I went in and he said, son, close the door.
I closed the door.
He says, you have to leave Gifford Hill.
I said, have I done something wrong?
He said, no.
He said, some of the contractors say
are saying that we give you the sand and gravel and the pipe is the reason you can beat them on the jobs, and you're hurting our business.
Said, you have some good equipment, some good people, and you just go in your own name.
But he says, you don't have any credit.
I said, I don't need any credit.
We was living in Sherman at that time, and I said,
$183,000 of E-bonds paid for.
And I checked my bank account yesterday, and I had about $195,000 in it.
He said, you don't understand.
You can't buy anything.
He said, you go to the M&P Bank, the president's a real good friend of yours, and you borrow $50,000 for 30 days and pay him the interest and pay it back, which I did.
And he said, then you go back in there the next day
And you borrow $100,000 for 30 days, and you pay them back.
I couldn't understand why I'd be paying Interstone money when I had all that money in that bank account.
But then I'd establish my credit, which is a rather unusual way to do it.
Yeah.
But you had never had occasion to borrow any money prior to that.
I didn't.
I wanted to work and give a real name because I got all their buying power.
And if I needed $50,000, that's all I'd do right there.
And in Dallas, deposit $50,000 in a certain bank wherever I was doing bidding.
And then, of course, the estimate was in Gifford Hill's name and went to them.
In Dallas, I never touched any money except write to payroll and draw what money I had to have to live on.
So what took place then in 48?
Oh, I did real good.
Did you then kind of sever connections with Gifford Hill?
No, no, no, no, no, no, no.
They just didn't bid for me.
I bid in my own name.
You bid in your own name.
Yeah, I had to.
I bid in my own name.
But up to that time, even though it was really your own company, if you were going to bid on a job to build a road or something, you would bid in the name of Gifford Hill.
Oh, yes, yes.
Did that so I could have their buying power, and then the people couldn't touch me that...
Since I was a superintendent, I wasn't supposed to give them anything.
You say the engineers were looking for a handout.
I don't want to say too much about that.
But, see, we worked in Louisiana, Arkansas, Mississippi, and everything, and they were really tough.
In fact, if you cut that off one minute, please, so I don't want to get this on.

Well, one of the most interesting things, I think, that happened in all our life, we were living in Henderson, Texas, and I was out on a job, and my brother called my wife and told me, told her that we must move to Sherman, Texas.
That day, they had gotten Perrin Field.
Perrin Field was the first area of fields that they built in the south before Pearl Harbor.
We started on the fourth day of July and finished up, oh, I'd say the latter part of October before Pearl Harbor.
Well, no, the latter part of November, and then December the 7th, Pearl Harbor.
And then at that time, we were working in Dallas building that North American plane plant parking area and the building and all.
So you were involved in the construction of Perrin Field.
I built half of it.
You had the contract.
Yeah, Gifford Hill.
Gifford Hill had the contract.
Yeah, but I owned this outfit at that time, 41.
But Bell and Braden at that time were in Amarillo, and it was a mile square.
So we cut it in two halfway from the east to the west, and I took the south end.
And we moved, oh, about 4 million yards of dirt there.
And at that time, there's no way to buy any equipment.
It was all frozen.
And we had to lease it, borrow it, do anything we could.
But we made it.
After 48, when your brother called you in and said you were going to have to leave Gifford Hill, did you then give your company your own name?
Oh, yeah.
E.B.
Hill.
E.B.
Hill.
E.B.
Hill Contractor.
It's not a stock company.
No, no.
Owned every bit of it.
So then we had an opportunity to buy the Caterpillar dealership here in Amarillo from R.B.
George in Dallas.
And my last job was at Lufkin in 51.
And then I started selling my equipment there.
And we bought a Caterpillar deal here in Amarillo, which was West Texas Equipment Company, a corporation.
And I owned about 51% of it, and this partner in Amarillo owned part of it.
And then the little manager out here owned, I think, 15 shares, something like that.
2,000 shares, what it was.
And then we ran that for, say, to 66, I think.
And then I had some trouble with my heart.
And my doctor told me, EB, you have too much pressure on you, you're going to die.
And my heart was 2 and 1 half inches too large.
So he gave me two years to sell out.
And after a year, then my heart was back normal.
And I've been doing real good since.
So you're still in the Caterpillar dealership?
No, no, no.
You sold that out?
I'm in the finance business.
I'm financing some of the customers, the good customers I had out there, not so much as I was.
I like the CDs now better than the other.
At 11.5% interest.
Where can you get a CD for 11.5%?
I get them all the time.
Well, it depends.
If you have enough to invest, I presume.
Yeah, you've got to have 100,000.
What would you say was your biggest job you ever handled in contracting?
Oh, the parent field.
The parent field was.
But the best job I ever had in my life, if you have been over from the Parker County line eight miles to Weatherford,
And down the bottom, there's these twin bridges, you know, right?
They're beautiful.
And pecan trees all around them and everything.
I built that in 1938.
And the equipment was very hard to come by.
And that was the first time I'd ever been west of Fort Worth.
Because a rock would tear your equipment up so bad, I stayed back in the dirt.
But I had a $282,000 job, and it was cheap.
50 cent rock, 15 cent dirt, $15 concrete.
It was cheap.
So I had four contractor friends told me that says, you can't do it for that money.
I said, oh, yes, I'm going to do it.
I said, Gifford Hill's going to make bond, and I'm going to build the job.
And I made 60.
I bought it.
and paid for everything on the job and made $64,000 cash.
And that kicked me over.
Then we moved to Henderson and got about a million and a quarter yards of dirt.
Did real good on it.
And then from then on, we could see daylight.
But we had some pretty tough times.
Well, getting started, when you did in one of the worst economic periods we've ever had,
Yeah, see, I went through 1919 and 1929.
And at the time when 29 came, it never did bother us.
We were building.
I was building.
I was superintendent for Gifford Hill.
We built 144 miles, the Cotton Belt Railroad from Mount Pleasant to Corsicana, moving about four and a quarter million yards of dirt.
We did it with mules, tractors, drag lines, shovels, every means in the world.
Dump cars.
And we did 50 and 60 foot cuts under traffic.
We had to carry the traffic as well as,
What we'd do, we'd take a cut through and lay what we called a shoe fly track around and put the traffic over there and tear up this line and then go down with the cut and just crisscross that away.
Lots of track land and stuff like that.
But we had five big outfits there.
And then in the 31, after everyone else had really hit, Gippert Hill wound up with a world of equipment.
No money.
So I was making $450 a month, an automobile, an expense account.
And my brother called me to Dallas, took my car, my expense account, and cut my salary to $175 a month.
It says go to Bell's, Tennessee.
That's right near Jackson.
It's 90 miles to the other side of Memphis, Tennessee.
And when I came home, I told my wife, my brother has to do this to me.
I'll never work for another person.
So it wasn't much over a year from then until I got my own out there.
And I did real well.
How much of a problem was it taking care of a whole bunch of mules that you used on your construction job when you first started?
Well, it wasn't any problem at all.
We had plenty of labor.
What was wrong?
when it rained for 10 days or something like that, and you couldn't.
And then every time that rain would hit the roof, I'm pardoned, no more sleep for me that night.
I spent lots of sleepless nights, that's all.
There's no problem.
Keeping the meals calm?
Keeping them fed.
Doctoring them all night.
Work them all day, and then we'd stay up all night and doctor them.
Crush ice and put on their heads.
Louisiana is terrible, you know, to have a brain concussion.
I had three young mules that I'd bought, and I watched them.
I'd stand them so I could watch them.
When they make them a step, you know that they're getting too hot.
But I had a man with a five-gallon bucket at one end and five gallons at the end, and it hit their nostrils.
Every load, it was dusty.
And I saw this mule make a misstep.
And before I could get...
They were about four of them here to the guest house down there.
Before I could get two of them, all three of them dropped dead in the harness.
That's hard to take.
That's one of the things I wouldn't want to go back through.
What would you say would be some of the principal developments in the technology of road building during the time that you were involved in road building?
Well, there was every change in the world.
Of course, we started out a little slip, you know, with two handles and two mules.
That's where we removed most of the dirt.
Then we came to the Fresno, you know, that has the dump.
And then we came to what they call the wheelers.
That was the worst piece of machinery in the world because the weight of all that dirt and everything were right on these mules' necks, and there's no way to protect it.
Oh, their necks got so bad.
I never owned one.
I said I'll never put one of my mules to that torture to have a wheeler.
I've never used a wheeler.
I've used a slip in a Fresnel.
Yeah, well, a wheeler,
That tongue, they've got to hold that.
And if that dirt is out here, all that weight's right on that tongue.
And the only way in the world to hold it up is for those mules' necks.
It's just terrible.
So you've come from that to really heavy equipment to move whatever you need to move.
Yeah, we started out, the first tractor I ever had was what they call a 60.
That's an old, well, kind of the chug-a-lug type, you know.
Then in 1935, I bought my first diesel, diesel 50.
It was...
50 horsepower, is the reason they call it that.
And of course, it was quite something, getting away from the gasoline and burning diesel.
Much cheaper and much better operated.
It runs smoother.
When, uh...
Did you ever have anything very much to do with the design of a road?
Oh, no.
I worked for the engineers when I was a kid, 15, 16 years old.
County engineers, you know, set stakes, and then when it rained, we'd have to work in the office, you know, and figure the volume, you know.
Yes, I've done some engineering quite a bit.
But not after you had gone to A&M.
You were always involved in construction work.
Never had anything to do with it.
The knowledge of being a contractor and starting out like we did is being able to know people, to know the ability of what they can do and get out of them what you should.
And a lot of people don't know that.
A lot of people think that people can just work continuously and never have to get up for breath, but that's not true.
Man has to rest a little bit once in a while.
And then some people can do some things and some people can't do things.
Some people can use a shovel and others can't use a shovel.
Some of them can use a hoe and some of them can't use it.
Some of them can use a axe.
And I think being able to know what a person can do helps you a lot in the construction business.
And another thing, I'm always, my organization, I take great pride that I don't believe that we ever put a yard of dirt in our life the wrong place.
When we picked it up, we put it where it belonged.
You knew where it was going before you picked it up.
Right.
That was number one.
Now, this superintendent, he's my bookkeeper now.
We were born and reared about six blocks from each other.
My birthday is the 1st of December.
His is the 16th of January.
I'm that much older than you.
But a scraper could come by him with a $2,500 tire on just flat, and he couldn't see it.
But if that man had come by with a half a load of dirt, he'd just have a tantrum.
And that's just part of it.
didn't come by with a half full.
It had to be all the way full.
Right.
Right.
And it had to go the right place.
Well, I imagine it costs just about as much to move it when it's half full as it does when it's all the way full.
Right.
At that man's time and that gas fuel and everything, it's just got to be sure that they're loaded.
Yeah.
Since you've been out of the Caterpillar dealership, what have you been involved in?
Financing.
Financing the customers of the Caterpillar.
Right.
Are you involved in any kind of social or political activities?
Not much.
Not much.
Not political.
I have a lot of friends in politics that I admire, but I've never been involved.
in politics, and they were so desired.
Earlier, you mentioned, I believe, while we had the machine off, that you went to London with the Former Students Association.
Oh, yes.
Was that a pretty enjoyable trip?
Wonderful.
Wonderful.
Have you done much other foreign travel?
Oh, yes.
Well, earlier you said you had a...
A boy from Lima, Peru that you tried to go see a couple of years ago, and he passed away.
We have a granddaughter that lives in Venezuela.
Caracas.
We spent 17 days there in February.
We're going back and spending Christmas.
We can't.
Here, you have to be gone in the winter months and see the first of April.
This garden and this yard, from then to the first of November, you might say, you're tied.
It's a full-time job.
Well, you can't get any help here.
You can get a help here and pay them $2.50 an hour and give them their time, pay them their time while they're eating lunch, feed them.
Next week, they won't be back.
There's more work here than there are people to do it.
I believe at one point you said, what, you have four daughters?
Three.
Three daughters.
And how many grandchildren?
Ten grandchildren.
Seven little girls and three little boys.
But you had no son of your own?
No.
I had a redefined son-in-law that was in Venice with me out there, and he was killed two years ago in July.
He was a shell jobber in Wichita Falls and that.
Charlotte's taken it over and just made a terrific success of it.
She has a 16-year-old boy and a 14-year-old boy and a 12-year-old girl.
So your daughters have some of your business equivalent, too?
She is quite a business figure.
And our oldest daughter, she's married to a dentist over here.
She had one of the brightest minds as far as figures, you know, about paying bills.
I have to show you this.
